    <!-- Add Activity -->

    <activity xml:id="act-number-guessing-log2">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <term>Work in pairs.</term> One person secretly picks a whole number from 1 to 64. The other person tries to find it by asking yes/no questions.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Play the game. Person A picks a number from 1 to 64 and keeps it secret. Person B asks yes/no questions to find it. Count how many questions Person B needs. Play twice and swap roles.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    Allow free play before guiding students. They may use many different strategies at first — this is fine. The goal is to get them curious about efficiency.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Share your question counts with the class. What was the fewest questions anyone used? Do you think it is always possible to guarantee finding the number in 6 questions or fewer?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <note component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    Expect a range of answers (often 6–15). The point of sharing is to spark curiosity: why do some students need fewer questions? Accept all answers here without resolving the question — the next tasks build towards it.
                </p>
            </note>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider this opening question: <q>Is the number greater than 32?</q> No matter whether the answer is yes or no, how many numbers are left as possibilities?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    If yes: numbers 33–64 remain (32 possibilities). If no: numbers 1–32 remain (32 possibilities). Either way, exactly half the numbers are eliminated. Ask students: what question should come next?
                </p>
            </solution>
            <note component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    Compare with a question like <q>Is it odd?</q> — that also splits into 32 each time, but subsequent questions are harder to plan. Guide students towards questions of the form <q>Is it greater than <m>k</m>?</q> as a reliable strategy.
                </p>
            </note>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Suppose you always ask a question that cuts the remaining possibilities exactly in half. Complete this table:
                </p>
                <tabular halign="center" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Questions asked</cell>
                        <cell>Numbers still possible</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row><cell>0</cell><cell>64</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>1</cell><cell>32</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>2</cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>3</cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>4</cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>5</cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>6</cell><cell></cell></row>
                </tabular>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <tabular halign="center" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Questions asked</cell>
                        <cell>Numbers still possible</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row><cell>0</cell><cell>64</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>1</cell><cell>32</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>2</cell><cell>16</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>3</cell><cell>8</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>4</cell><cell>4</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>5</cell><cell>2</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>6</cell><cell>1</cell></row>
                </tabular>
                <p>
                    After 6 questions, exactly 1 number remains — the answer is known with certainty.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Write the number of remaining possibilities after <m>k</m> questions as a power of 2. What is the connection between 64 and the number 6?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    After <m>k</m> questions, <m>64 \div 2^k</m> numbers remain. When <m>k = 6</m>, this is <m>64 \div 2^6 = 1</m>. The connection is <m>64 = 2^6</m>, so 6 questions suffice.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Using your pattern, complete this table for different starting ranges, then express the result using a logarithm:
                </p>
                <tabular halign="center" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Range of numbers</cell>
                        <cell>Minimum questions guaranteed</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row><cell>1 to 2</cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>1 to 4</cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>1 to 8</cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>1 to 16</cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>1 to 32</cell><cell></cell></row>
                    <row><cell>1 to 64</cell><cell>6</cell></row>
                </tabular>
                <p>
                    For a range of 1 to <m>n</m>, write a formula for the minimum number of questions needed (assume <m>n</m> is a power of 2).
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    The answers are 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6. For a range of 1 to <m>n = 2^k</m>, the minimum number of questions is <m>k = \log_2 n</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
            <note component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    If students struggle to see the logarithm, ask: <q>If <m>2^k = n</m>, how do you solve for <m>k</m>?</q> This connects directly to the definition of logarithm from earlier in the chapter.
                </p>
            </note>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A friend picks a number from 1 to 1000. What is the minimum number of yes/no questions you need to guarantee finding it? Use the change of base formula <m>\log_2 x = \dfrac{\log_{10} x}{\log_{10} 2}</m> and a calculator.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    <m>\log_2 1000 = \dfrac{\log_{10} 1000}{\log_{10} 2} = \dfrac{3}{\log_{10} 2} \approx 9.97</m>. Since we need a whole number of questions, we round up to 10. Students can verify: <m>2^{10} = 1024 \geq 1000</m>, while <m>2^9 = 512 \lt 1000</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </activity>

