    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            Logarithmic equations are powerful tools that can help us understand and solve a wide range of real-life problems, from population growth to sound intensity. By applying logarithmic properties and calculations, we can make sense of complex phenomena and make informed decisions based on data.
        </p>
    </insight> 

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
         <p>
              In <m>2010</m>, Haiti experienced an earthquake whose intensity was <m>10^7</m> times the reference intensity <m>I_0</m>. The Richter scale is defined by:
         </p>
         <p>
            <m> M = \log_{10}\left(\frac{I}{I_0}\right)</m>
         </p>
         <p>
            Where:
         </p>
            <p>
            <ul>
                <li><m>M</m> is the magnitude of the earthquake on the Richter scale.</li>
                <li><m>I</m> is the intensity of the earthquake.</li>
                <li><m>I_0</m> is the reference intensity, (the smallest intensity that can be detected by seismographs).</li>
            </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Determine the magnitude of the earthquake on the Richter scale.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                 Given <m>\frac{I}{I_0} = 10^7</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                While the Richter scale formula is:
            </p>
            <p>
                 <m>M = \log_{10}\left(\frac{I}{I_0}\right)</m>. 
            </p>
               <p>
                  <md>
                     <intertext>Therefore substwitute the given values into the formula you have:</intertext>
                     <mrow>M \amp= \log_{10}\left(10^7\right)</mrow>
                     <intertext>Use the law <m>\log_{10}(10^n)=n</m>:</intertext>
                     <mrow>M \amp= 7</mrow>
                  </md>
               </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the magnitude of the earthquake on the Richter scale is <m>7</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The intensity of a sound is measured in decibels (dB) and is given by the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>I = 10 \times \log_{10}(P/P_0)</md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Where <m>I</m> is the intensity in decibels, <m>P</m> is the power of the sound, and <m>P_0</m> is the reference power (the threshold of hearing). If a sound has a power of <m>1</m> watt and the reference power is <m>10^{-12}</m> watts, what is the intensity of the sound in decibels?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Substituting <m>P = 1</m> and <m>P_0 = 10^{-12}</m>:
            </p>
            <md>
                <mrow>I \amp= 10 \times \log_{10}\!\left(\frac{1}{10^{-12}}\right)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 10 \times \log_{10}(10^{12})</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 10 \times 12</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 120</mrow>
            </md>
            <p>
                Therefore, the intensity of the sound is <m>120</m> decibels.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A radioactive substance decays at a rate proportional to its current amount, with the amount <m>P(t)</m> of substance in grams at time <m>t</m> years give by:
                <md>
                    P(t) = P_0 \times 2^{-\frac{t}{5}}
                </md>
                where <m>P_0</m> is the initial mass (in grams).
            </p>
            <p>
                How long will it take for a sample of <m>100</m> grams to decay to <m>25</m> grams?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p> Substituting <m>P_0 = 100</m> and <m>P(t) = 25</m>:
            </p>
            <md>
                <mrow>25 \amp= 100 \times 2^{-\frac{t}{5}}</mrow>
                <intertext>Divide both sides by 100:</intertext>
                <mrow>0.25 \amp= 2^{-\frac{t}{5}}</mrow>
                <intertext>Take <m>\log_2</m> of both sides. Since <m>\log_2(0.25) = \log_2(1/4) = -2</m>:</intertext>
                <mrow>-2 \amp= -\frac{t}{5}</mrow>
                <intertext>Multiply both sides by 5:</intertext>
                <mrow>t \amp= 10</mrow>
            </md>
            <p>
                Therefore, it will take <m>10</m> years for the sample to decay to <m>25</m> grams.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

